            "creation_date": 1355257280,
            "body": "<p>A good place to start is with a Diagram.<\/p>\n\n<p>I imagine your activity class is quite long and complex, from the information you have given in your question, i'm guessing that you have some sort of game board, that sounds like a potential item to refactor. <\/p>\n\n<p>try this book <a href=\"http://www.headfirstlabs.com/books/hfdp/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.headfirstlabs.com/books/hfdp/<\/a> while it is not the best or most definitive guide to design it offers good entry level information and help.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13827875,
            "question_id": 13827732
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/75671bb3f0c157f26824dd852f56a13a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1324601,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1269727,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1269727/toadzky",
                "reputation": 3846,
                "display_name": "toadzky",
                "accept_rate": 80
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1355257289,
            "creation_date": 1355257289,
            "body": "<p>All code to update UI elements goes in the Activity or View itself. You can't access any of that from the POJO. It sounds like you, like so many, are trying to make a game. I would suggest you learn Java first, then Android, THEN try to make a game. Don't start with something as complicated as a game.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13827877,
            "question_id": 13827732
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cda3d3f8ce3c14627cf1cf269a25245e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1895526,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1712593,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1712593/marius-m",
                "reputation": 496,
                "display_name": "Marius M"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1355257910,
            "creation_date": 1355257910,
            "body": "<p>I guess you started up a bit too far ahead, browse a little through oop, separation of concerns and mvc; anyway,given your question - the updateBoard() method should not be in your ScoreClock class, it should be in your Activity class which plays the controller in this case.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13828040,
            "question_id": 13827732
        }
